				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2203795&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182394" alt="Kalinin" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2203795)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;" >Kalinin</a></span> <span class="odate time_1457841865 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">13 Mar 2016 04:04</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2471817">
									

<p>Two major issues with this:</p>
<ul>
<li>The format makes no sense to me whatsoever. Insofar as AWCY is a cogent group of any sort, and I have doubts that they're organized to that extent in pretty much all possible interpretations, I cannot imagine them keeping standardized records like what's being written up here. Not to mention records that feel an awful lot like a mainlist article. The transition from official to casual can work in other contexts, I feel, but here it just highlights the issues with the formatting. That's probably not particularly fair to the author, but it has a pretty big impact on my reading experience.</li>
<li>I don't really care for the clear cause-and-effect relationship between the phenomenon and the artist's motivations for creating it. I feel that artwork comes from a more complex place than &quot;I am feeling X and I therefore will Y&quot;, and this isn't really convincing me that someone out there had an experience in mind to inflict on humanity that required subverting the rules of reality. Again, this might not be fair, because I can see the role that this playing in advancing the overall narrative of the story. I appreciate that the narrative is present (there hasn't been one in some cases for other teams in this contest), and that this is moving it forward, but as a standalone piece, it's just not working for me.</li>
</ul>

							</div>

								
					
