				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/themightymcb" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4483018); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=4483018&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182394" alt="TheMightyMcB" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=4483018)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/themightymcb" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(4483018); return false;" >TheMightyMcB</a></span> <span class="odate time_1543238722 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Nov 2018 13:25</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4068258">
									

<blockquote>
<p>◾500&#160;mL blood plasma from an SCP-1237-1-L-positive individual (Type O- preferred)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Slight issue with that biologically. Blood plasma is already universal regarding transfer from one individual to another. Blood typing refers to red blood cells, specifically proteins (or lack thereof) that are on the outside of the cells. The most important are the A, B, and Rh factors, hence why a normal blood type will have A, B, AB, or O (A and B absent), followed by a + or - for the Rh factor. With no red blood cells present in fresh frozen plasma, blood type doesn't matter. Most people who have a PhD (or even a BS) in a science would know that, so the issue is definitely jarring to anybody who would notice it.</p>
<p>EDIT: Also, the original article makes it very clear that there are likely less than 10 individuals in the entire world at any given point who are both SCP-1237-1 positive and are lucid dreamers, so the chances of finding one who is all of that that ALSO has a decently scarce blood type (2.55% of the world is O-) are pretty damn astronomical.</p>
<p>EDIT MKII: Blood plasma is pretty much just a solution that our other blood cells sit in. It has some pH buffers, CO<sub>2</sub> waste, some proteins, some ions, and glucose, but that's about it. It's 95% water. No genetic material, and nothing in the original SCP-1237 article indicates that the genetic sequence that makes you an SCP-1237-1 instance codes for proteins in the plasma. There is nothing to lead me to believe that giving somebody SCP-1237-1-L plasma has any chance whatsoever of giving them the properties of such a person, even for a short time.</p>
<p>TL;DR: Lots of bad biology going on here.</p>

